Crimea and Sudetenland, same fight?
BRUSSELS – The annexation of Crimea by Russia constitutes the most serious example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has witnessed since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly today fashionable to downplay the importance of the "Lessons of Munich" when discussing this episode where Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier yielded to Hitler's demands on Czechoslovakia in order to pacify the Führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of invasion of sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, following the takeover of Georgian regions Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might well regret their inaction.
In Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – for example, expulsion from the G8 – could be seen as humorous if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union to be the most severe catastrophe of modern times, the man striving relentlessly to revive a fallen Russian empire.
If the West intends to be taken seriously, it will need to act with the same determination that Putin demonstrates.
Many of the president's successes within his imperialistic project have cost him virtually nothing so far.
His initiative for an Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to attract a number of resource-rich states such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation forced it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And now, the most valuable geopolitical prize of all – Ukraine – could fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "stops being an empire," as explained by former US national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, with a subverted and subordinate Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the vast majority of Ukrainians have no desire to join Putin's empire, it is likely that the country led by Russian President will now be a highly militarized state, akin to a Soviet Union without the Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community's reaction matches the degree of adventurism demonstrated by Putin.
Summits cancellations, trade agreement proposals, and other participation in forums as ineffective as the G8 will not suffice.
Only actions involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions that could affect Russian citizens – who, let us remember, continue to re-elect Putin in power – can allow us to hope that the Kremlin will leave its expansionist trajectory.
What kind of sanctions could these be?
Firstly, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles strait to Russian transport, as it did after the 2008 Russo-Georgian war.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea to prevent America from intervening, although it now appears clearly that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships but also to all commercial ships heading to Russian Black Sea ports.
The impact on the Russian economy – as well as on Putin’s military ambitions – would be considerable.
Turkey is allowed to close the Dardanelles under an amendment added in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Thus, Turkey could turn against Putin the rationale he invoked to justify the annexation of Crimea – namely, that it would protect ethnic Russians living there – by claiming instead to be safeguarding his own Turkish citizens of Tatar descent, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make an in-air turnaround en route to Kiev to provide support to the new interim government.
The prime minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan, who, like Putin, is not exactly a soft touch, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian shipping – until Putin withdraws all his troops from Crimea back to their bases, which would be those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to have the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in case Russia tried to intimidate it.
Secondly, US President Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions on Russia as he did on Iran over its nuclear program.
These sanctions indeed severely damaged the Iranian economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system to all banks doing business with Russian banks or companies would generate unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russians must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power is based on his promise to end the scarcity of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist path could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, Obama could remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
To Putin, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was truly a disaster, but for China, it constituted the most formidable geopolitical windfall one can imagine.
In an instant, this empire that had stolen millions of hectares of Chinese territory over centuries and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation simply vanished.
Since then, Central Asian independent states, and Ukraine itself, have become important trading partners for China.
The invasion of Georgia by Russia seriously disappointed China, as evidenced at the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held following the war (this regional group comprising several former Soviet states bordering both China and Mother Russia).
Russia tried to get the SCO to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
However, the organization expressed disagreement.
Indeed, the Central Asian countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – could never have stood up against the Kremlin without China's support.
It is now up to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's provocations.
The true test of China's claim to be a genuine and responsible player within the international community will indeed soon play out at the United Nations.
Will China support this clear violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other avenues for sanctions are also being considered.
Each Russian leader could thus have their visas refused or canceled.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, particularly those that have been cleaned through associates close to Putin.
This will only fail when the pain becomes unbearable, especially for the elites.
The cost of inaction could well prove significant.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on America’s promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
In addition, when Ukraine abandoned its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the UK, France, and Russia) would guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea remains annexed, no one can blame Ukraine if it decides to renuclearize its defense (which it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous phrase, "You had the choice between war and humiliation.
You chose humiliation, and you will have war." Today, Obama and other Western leaders are facing a similar choice.
If they were to choose humiliation, we can be certain that the bold Putin will eventually serve them another war at some point.
